# BIXBG Chatbot — IDE Operational Rules

> These rules are absolute constraints. Code that violates any rule below is wrong by definition.
> Read this file before generating any code for this project.

---

## Project Context

This project is a web chatbot for **Belle idee x Bella gente (BIXBG)**, an internal tool used exclusively by the founder (Matteo) to qualify experience ideas, structure them creatively, and identify partner/sponsor profiles. The system is a **multi-agent architecture** composed of 4 AI agents (Manager, Compass, Architect, Bridge) that route user messages to the correct specialist via a two-step LLM pipeline. The stack is **Next.js (App Router) + React + Tailwind CSS**, deployed on Vercel, using the **Vercel AI SDK** and the **Claude API (Anthropic)** as the LLM provider.

---

## File Structure

Place every file in the exact path specified. Do not create new top-level directories without explicit instruction.

```
/app/
  page.tsx                        # Root page — chat UI entry point
  layout.tsx                      # Root layout (fonts, global metadata)
  globals.css                     # Global styles

/app/api/
  chat/
    route.ts                      # Single API route — all LLM calls go here

/knowledge-base/
  shared.md                       # Shared KB injected into every agent
  compass.md                      # Vertical KB for Compass only
  architect.md                    # Vertical KB for Architect only
  bridge.md                       # Vertical KB for Bridge only

/app/components/
  ChatWindow.tsx                  # Main chat container component
  MessageBubble.tsx               # Individual message display component
  AgentIndicator.tsx              # Shows active agent name + color badge
  ChatInput.tsx                   # Message input + submit button

/lib/
  agents.ts                       # Agent definitions: names, colors, prompt loaders
  manager.ts                      # Manager routing logic (LLM call + JSON parse)
  kb-loader.ts                    # Reads .md files from /knowledge-base/ at runtime

/prompts/
  compass.ts                      # System prompt for Compass (as exported string)
  architect.ts                    # System prompt for Architect
  bridge.ts                       # System prompt for Bridge
  manager-prompt.ts               # System prompt for Manager
                                    # NOTE: named manager-prompt.ts (not manager.ts) to avoid
                                    # import ambiguity with /lib/manager.ts

.env.local                        # API key — never committed, never imported client-side
.gitignore                        # Must include .env.local
```

---

## Naming Conventions

- Name **files and folders** in `kebab-case`. Example: `kb-loader.ts`, `knowledge-base/`.
- Name **React components** in `PascalCase`. Example: `ChatWindow`, `MessageBubble`.
- Name **TypeScript interfaces and types** in `PascalCase` with a descriptive noun. Example: `AgentName`, `RoutingDecision`, `ChatMessage`.
- Name **functions and variables** in `camelCase`. Example: `loadKnowledgeBase`, `currentAgent`, `routingDecision`.
- Name **environment variables** in `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`, prefixed with the provider name. Example: `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.
- Name **agent identifiers** in lowercase string literals only: `"compass"`, `"architect"`, `"bridge"`. Never use uppercase or abbreviations.
- Name **exported constants** in `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`. Example: `AGENT_COLORS`, `MAX_HISTORY_MESSAGES`.

---

## Mandatory Patterns

### API Route (`/app/api/chat/route.ts`)
- Wrap the entire route handler body in a `try/catch` block. Return a structured JSON error response with HTTP 500 on any uncaught exception.
- Validate that the incoming request body contains `message` (non-empty string) and `history` (array) before making any LLM call. Return HTTP 400 with a descriptive error if validation fails.
- Call the Manager LLM first (classification). Parse its JSON response before proceeding. Validate that the parsed `agent` field is one of `'compass' | 'architect' | 'bridge'`. If JSON parsing fails OR the agent value is invalid, log the raw Manager output server-side and default to `'compass'` as the fallback agent — never return HTTP 500 to the client for a Manager failure. A broken UX is worse than a graceful fallback.
- Load the KB files using `fs.promises.readFile` with `path.join(process.cwd(), 'knowledge-base', filename)`. Wrap in `try/catch`. If a KB file is missing, log a warning and continue with an empty string — do not crash the route. Never use `__dirname` or relative paths — they break in the Vercel serverless environment.
- Truncate `history` to the last 20 messages before injecting it into any LLM call. Define this limit as the exported constant `MAX_HISTORY_MESSAGES = 20` in `/lib/agents.ts`.
- Return the streaming response using `streamText()` + `.toDataStreamResponse()` from the Vercel AI SDK v3+. Do NOT use `StreamingTextResponse` — it was removed in AI SDK v3. Set `x-agent`, `x-agent-color`, and `x-agent-name` as response headers on the returned Response object before returning it.
- Never log the full API key. Log only the first 8 characters for diagnostics.

### Frontend (`/app/components/`)
- Every React component must be a named export (not default export). This makes refactoring and tree-shaking explicit.
- Wrap the `ChatWindow` component in a React `ErrorBoundary`. Display a visible fallback UI on error.
- Use the `useChat` hook from the Vercel AI SDK to manage conversation history and streaming state. The `useChat` hook stores state in the React tree and resets on page reload — this satisfies the session-based, non-persistent requirement. Do not use `localStorage`, `sessionStorage`, or any external store (Redux, Zustand, etc.).
- Read the active agent identity from response headers using the `onResponse` callback of `useChat`. Store the parsed agent identity in a separate `useState` variable. Never hardcode agent names or colors in component state.
- Derive the active agent name and color from the response headers returned by `/api/chat`. Never hardcode agent state in the frontend.
- Disable the submit button and input field while a streaming response is in progress. Re-enable them only when streaming is complete.

### Knowledge Base Loading (`/lib/kb-loader.ts`)
- Read all `.md` files using `fs.promises.readFile` at request time (runtime read, not build time).
- Export a single function `loadKnowledgeBase(agent: AgentName): Promise<{ shared: string; vertical: string }>` that returns both the shared KB and the vertical KB for the given agent.
- Add a JSDoc comment on every exported function describing its inputs, outputs, and the behavior on error.

### Prompts (`/prompts/`)
- Export each system prompt as a plain TypeScript string constant. Example: `export const COMPASS_PROMPT = \`...\``.
- Do not construct system prompts dynamically at runtime. All prompt text is static and defined at import time.

### General
- Add a JSDoc comment above every exported function, regardless of how obvious the function appears.
- Use named exports everywhere. Default exports are forbidden.
- Use `async/await` for all asynchronous operations. Do not use `.then()/.catch()` chains.

---

## Forbidden Patterns

- **Never make LLM API calls from the frontend.** All calls to Claude (or any LLM provider) must go through `/app/api/chat/route.ts`. Violation exposes the API key to the client.
- **Never import `process.env` values in any file under `/app/components/` or any client-side module.** Environment variables are server-only.
- **Never commit `.env.local`.** It must always be present in `.gitignore`. If this file appears in a diff, something is wrong.
- **Never use `localStorage` or `sessionStorage`.** Conversation history is session-based React state. Persistence is explicitly out of scope.
- **Never add a database, ORM, or persistent storage layer.** No Prisma, no Supabase, no Redis, no SQLite. Stateless by design.
- **Never add user authentication or session management.** No NextAuth, no Clerk, no JWT. The tool is single-user by design.
- **Never send the entire unbounded conversation history to the LLM.** Always truncate to `MAX_HISTORY_MESSAGES` before any API call. Unbounded history causes context window overflow (Risk R1).
- **Never route to a non-existent agent.** The Manager's `agent` field must be one of: `"compass"`, `"architect"`, `"bridge"`. Validate this in code before using the value.
- **Never skip the Manager call.** Every user message must be classified by the Manager before the specialist agent is called. Hard-coding which agent responds is forbidden.
- **Never name an agent in user-visible text.** Components must not hardcode strings like `"Bridge"` or `"Compass"` in rendered output — always derive them from the response headers.
- **Never add analytics, tracking, or logging services.** No Mixpanel, no Sentry, no PostHog. Explicitly out of scope.
- **Never use a default export — with one exception.** `page.tsx` and `layout.tsx` must use `export default` as required by the Next.js App Router framework. All other files in this project use named exports exclusively.
- **Never use `.then()/.catch()` chains.** Use `async/await` with `try/catch` exclusively.
- **Never add an admin panel, settings page, or configuration UI.** The only page is the chat interface.

---

## Libraries and Dependencies

### USE

| Package | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `next` (latest stable) | Framework — App Router |
| `react` / `react-dom` | UI rendering |
| `ai` (Vercel AI SDK v3+, latest stable) | LLM streaming via `streamText` + `toDataStreamResponse`, `useChat` hook |
| `@anthropic-ai/sdk` | Claude API client (server-side only) |
| `tailwindcss` | Utility-first CSS |
| `typescript` | Type safety across the project |
| `fs` (Node built-in) | Reading `.md` KB files at runtime |

### DO NOT USE

| Package | Reason |
|---|---|
| Any database client (Prisma, Drizzle, Mongoose…) | No database — explicitly out of scope |
| `next-auth`, Clerk, Auth.js, or any auth library | No authentication — explicitly out of scope |
| `zustand`, `jotai`, `redux` | State management beyond React `useState` is not needed |
| `langchain` or `llamaindex` | No RAG, no embeddings, no vector store — static KB only |
| `axios` | Use native `fetch` — no additional HTTP client needed |
| Any analytics SDK (Mixpanel, Segment, PostHog…) | Analytics is out of scope |
| Any payment SDK (Stripe, Paddle…) | Payments are out of scope |

> If a dependency not on this list appears necessary, stop and ask before installing it.

---

## Security

- Store the API key **only** in `.env.local` under the variable name `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`. This file must not be committed to Git.
- Access `process.env.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` **only** inside `/app/api/chat/route.ts` or files imported exclusively by server-side modules. Never access it in any component or client module.
- Validate and sanitize all incoming request bodies in the API route before use. Reject requests with unexpected or malformed fields with HTTP 400.
- Do not reflect raw user input directly into LLM system prompts. User messages go only into the `messages` array (not the system prompt), exactly as the Vercel AI SDK expects.
- Configure the Next.js API route to accept requests only from the same origin. Do not add permissive CORS headers.
- Never log full request bodies containing user conversation history. Log only routing decisions (agent name, reason) for debugging.
- Do not expose internal error stack traces to the client response. Return a generic error message to the client; log the full error server-side only.

---

## Code Style

- **Maximum function length:** 40 lines. If a function exceeds 40 lines, split it into named helper functions.
- **Indentation:** 2 spaces. No tabs.
- **Semicolons:** Required at the end of every statement.
- **Quotes:** Single quotes for all strings in TypeScript/JavaScript. Double quotes only inside JSX attribute values.
- **Trailing commas:** Required in multi-line arrays and objects.
- **Line length:** Maximum 100 characters per line.
- **TypeScript strictness:** Enable `strict: true` in `tsconfig.json`. No `any` types unless explicitly unavoidable — in which case add an inline comment explaining why.
- **JSON.parse typing:** `JSON.parse()` returns `any`. Never use the result directly — always apply a runtime validation guard before casting to a typed interface. Example: check that `result.agent` is a member of `VALID_AGENTS` before casting `result as RoutingDecision`.

### Comments — Mandatory
- Add a JSDoc block above every exported function, type, and constant.
- Add an inline comment on every `try/catch` block explaining what specific error it guards against.
- Add a comment above every LLM call explaining which agent is being called and what its expected output format is.

### Comments — Forbidden
- Do not add comments that restate what the code already clearly expresses. Example: `// increment i` above `i++` is forbidden.
- Do not leave `// TODO` or `// FIXME` comments in committed code. Resolve them before committing.
- Do not add commented-out code blocks. Delete unused code; version control handles history.
